Utterances.UttText: Subjective: Mr.
Cage is a 47 year old man with a 5 year history of hypertension who presents to clinic today for worsening chest pain.

Phrases.PhraseText: a 47 year old man with a 5 year history of hypertension

Utterances.UttText: He states that he first noticed the pain 4 months ago where he would have episodes of "twinges of pain" on exertion that would only last 1-2 seconds and then go away spontaneously; however, now it has gotten to the point where 3 days ago he was taking in some groceries from his car and he felt a "deep ache" that was "heavy" in the same area of his chest.

Phrases.PhraseText: gotten to the point where 3 days ago
in the same area of his chest.

Utterances.UttText: He had to rest in his car and then pain went away after a couple of minutes.

Phrases.PhraseText: away after a couple of minutes.

Utterances.UttText: The pain is in the middle of his chest and does not radiate anywhere.

Phrases.PhraseText: is in the middle of his chest

Utterances.UttText: He denies any SOB, HA, or abdominal pain associated with the chest pain, but states that he did feel lightheaded during the episode.
Medications: Chlorthalidone 25mg, Oral, Daily and Lisinopril 10mg Oral Daily.
Allergies: Denies any  PMHx: Diagnosed with hypertension 5 years ago.
Sees his PCP once a year and last saw them 6 months ago.
Surgical Hx: None FHx: Father had an MI in his 40s and had bypass surgery after.
Died at age 72.
Mother had HTN and died from a pulmonary embolism at age 60.
SHx: Works at Capital One and denies stress at job.
Has smoked a pack of cigarettes a day for about 20 years and drinks 2-3 glasses of wine every weekend.

MappingCandidates.CandidatePreferred: Life Expectancy Greater than Twenty Years

Utterances.UttText: Denies any illicit drug use.
Objective: Vitals: T 98.0F P 85 R 14 BP 150/92 Physical Exam: Heart: RRR, no murmurs, gallops, or rubs.

Phrases.PhraseText: T 98.0F P 85 R 14 BP 150/92 Physical Exam

Utterances.UttText: No tenderness of chest, Pulses 2+ bilaterally in Lower and upper extremities Lungs: CTABL, no wheezing or crackles.
No increased work of breathing Abdominal: No tenderness, guarding, or masses in all quadrants Assessment: Mr.
Cage is our 47 yo man with a past history of hypertension presenting today for 3 days of severe mid-chest pain on exertion.
